\begin_layout Title
Status consumption and intertemporal substitution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract

\shape italic
A model for status consumption is derived based on the framework for intertempor
al consumption choice.
 Status is endogenised as states of financial stability and included as
 part of the consumer's utility in a model where the consumer balances her
 needs for quality in the present with the potential of higher status (state)
 through savings for assets in the future.
 Theoretical and numerical solutions are discussed before estimation of
 the model from the Tanzanian LSMS consumption microdata (years 2010, 2012
 and 2014).
 Possible refinements of the model for decision under uncertainty are discussed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a conventional analysis of demand, one uses the prices and quantities
 observed of the items to understand the relative importance of commodities
 with respect to each other.
 The demand for individual goods is often aggregated into commodities to
 compare the demand with its past values or values in a different population
 - thus providing a sense of quality for a particular commodity.
 Viewing status consumption as an instance of high-quality consumption,
 if one were to use the measures of quality from the demand literature to
 measure status-related consumption, a detailed set of market prices of
 the goods within every commodity would be needed.
 The data on market prices is hardly available at local levels in most consumer
 surveys - compelling us to use the so-called hedonic approach - arguing
 that the characteristics of the commodity are what consumers evaluate in
 forms of price.
 While demand literature often uses market characteristics or shadow prices
 for such analyses of quality for a particular commodity, the studies on
 conspicuous consumption tend to explore a specific instance of status consumpti
on instead.
 Here, conspicuous consumption is expected to occur through a certain type
 of (visible) goods that are meant to be futile for the general needs of
 the consumer.
 This assumption allows us to use to the separability of demand for visible
 goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to extend the concept of visible consumption in the developing
 economies, we use the framework of demand analysis arguing that the framework
 could explain status consumption in a more general context.
 While such a model might not benefit from the tractability that the models
 for visible consumption benefit from, the estimates of wealth of the consumer
 (e.g.
 asset ownership in consumer data), if available, may allow us to observe
 how quality across commodities is consumed with respect to the wealth of
 the consumer.
 A general sense of status consumption - as we argue - must come from a
 combination of higher quality across commodities and a stable ownership
 of wealth or assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To elaborate the model, we enhance the framework for intertemporal consumer
 choice by adding long-term incentives and near-term demand for quality.
 In what could be seen as an attempt to refine the permanent income approach
 (which vigorously ignores all non-monetary wealth), we model the consumption
 on quality as sensitive to the perception of how (subjectively) probable
 a future state of financial security is to a consumer.
 In doing so, we use the assets (durable items) owned as an indicator of
 wealth (also because the data available on income may be poor in economies
 with a significant informal sector) and the high quality commodities as
 the consumer's attempt to improve one's perceived status.
 Arguing that consumption is myopic and depends on the perception of status
 in a near-term while savings are cumulative in an intertemporal model for
 consumer choice, we let the representative consumer in the model optimise
 utility inclusive of status - which is obtained by owned assets (including
 skills and characteristics that are acquired over multiple generations)
 and the quality of consumption.
 Arguing that the signalling benefit a consumer derives from consumption
 - in any sense - must come out of either high-priced non-durable consumption
 or long-term durable consumption, we view the signaling as the utility
 obtained from the consumption of quality and owned assets over time.
 Taking an approach different from the PIH, we consider how types of non-monetar
y wealth may matter towards the perception of risk (monetary or non-monetary)
 and attempt to relate the substitution between saving for assets and consumptio
n of quality in the life-time of the consumer to the long-term growth in
 the consumer's material wealth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key variables that the econometric analyses are concerned with are i)
 the extent to which the consumers maintain their habits of purchasing quality
 ii) the extent to which they choose to save for future assets rather than
 to overspend on higher quality in the current time period (measured simply
 as the distance - in monetary terms - from the cost of basic needs) and
 lastly iii) a measure of basic needs themselves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A consideration of the cost of assets available to the consumer is of particular
 interest if we wish to compare status-related consumption in two economies
 with disparate levels of economic development (e.g.
 a developed economy and a developing economy).
 The distribution of assets - which may vary significantly in a developing
 economy from the distribution in a developed economy - provide us a way
 to compare the contexts of status consumption in the two economies.
 For a set of assets (long-term durable goods) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{D}$
\end_inset

 ordered by increasing cost, the difference in successive costs i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta d_{j}=d_{j}-d_{j-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{j}\in\mathscr{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}<d_{j}\forall(i<j)$
\end_inset

 may be much higher relative to the cost of quality consumption in one economy
 relative to that in the other.
 These may have disparate effects on consumer choice in the two economies
 as the costlier long-term assets may discourage savings for the future
 (the consumer may give up hopes of acquiring assets if she is to remain
 in a low income group relative to asset costs) and the perceptions of high
 mobility may encourage the consumer to overspend on quality in the short-term
 (matching one's consumption to one's perceived status).
 As assets have a more definite impact on the consumer's secure long-term
 growth (assets being a stronger indicator the stability of her income),
 in equilibrium, the consumer would balance the more uncertain perception
 of her status with the more certain expected value of savings in her lifetime.
 Thus if income is assumed to follow a process 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 and the consumer spending on her needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is known, then observing the proportion of consumer's spending on quality
 (which also determines the savings rate for durable goods in the intertemporal
 settings due to the total income constraint) with respect to the measures
 of wealth can help us comment on the contexts of status consumption in
 the two economies.
 This we believe is key to understanding status consumption across economies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the specification of an intertemporal model for status consumption, we
 relate the spending on quality and on assets to two different uncertainties.
 The probability associated with the first uncertainty is due to the subjective
 view of the consumer of her own future states of wealth.
 The probability functions corresponding to the consumer's perceptions that
 match their expenditures on quality (i.e.
 the first uncertainty) are fundamentally guesses and may be subject to
 socio-political conditions more rather the long-term economic concerns.
 The subjective probabilities of the consumer however need to be coherent
 with the economy's long-term growth which is associated with the second
 uncertainty in the model.
 In a limited context of the current chapter, we provide a non-stochastic
 model defining the parameters in the Euler Equation for asset growth that
 are controlled by the consumer.
 In the basic model we provide in the chapter, an exogenous non- stochastic
 process for income is specified\SpecialChar endofsentence
 The econometric methods are then derived
 based on the intertemporal model extended for quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, we attempt to view status-related consumption in a conventional
 model for consumer demand - using the availability of asset costs in an
 economy and a definition of quality.
 We justify an interpretation of status consumption from quality and assets
 based on the assertion that for a rational consumer to spend on status
 consumption, she must see some status utility from consumption in the long-term
 or the short-term.
 As the goal of separating oneself from others through consumption (when
 all else fails) is effectively to minimise one's own perceived risk (if
 not the actual risk) of departure from the high-income group, status consumptio
n is likely to exist for every consumer in an economy where social stratificatio
n exists - thus generalising our model for status consumption across all
 consumers.
 Based on this model for status, we can argue that the consumer's focus
 on consumption may be more pronounced in societies undergoing economic
 upheavals (e.g.
 introduction to global markets, industrialisation), where the poorer social
 identities may try to cross previously imposed barriers through consumption
 (through a bandwagon effect) while those with richer social identities
 attempt to guard their status through consumption (a snob effect).
 To compare the status consumption in any two countries using our model,
 we seek econometric methods relying on parameters measuring consumer behaviour
 that are invariant with respect to the macroeconomic differences in the
 two respective economies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the discussions related to the specification of a model, we have made
 a conscious attempt to not take an ideological stance on whether status
 consumption is wasteful or a necessary artifact of the belief in social
 mobility.
 Thus instead of claiming whether status shows the consumers' long-termism
 or their short-termism, ours is merely an attempt to endogenise the role
 that social identities, long-term asset ownership and other types of wealth
 may play in consumption - particularly since we wish to seek a framework
 general enough to be used to test the existence of status consumption in
 the developing countries.
 The econometric methods that we have developed, interpret quality as the
 distance of expensive nondurable consumption from the minimum cost of needs
 and use the model assumption that any status value in the short-run can
 only be achieved through relative quality of consumption.
 The two primary goals that we wish to accomplish with the particular model
 for status consumption - are i) to test whether the preference for quality
 increases with rise in income and urbanisation (indicated by the expansion
 of consumer basket) and ii) to see if preferences for quality change across
 populations segregated through levels of development, economic strata or
 social identities within an economy.
\end_layout

