LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonEconConsumer"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\bar under
It is worth clarifying that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 itself cannot be a part of utility.
 The model needs to represent benefit derived from 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 into consumption - which is what the consumer benefits from.
 So except for status purpose, education cannot give utility to the consumer.
 In the stochastic environment, this would affect 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 but in a non-stochastic model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 does not influence consumption directly.
 The only obvious way to do this is to let consumer have a rebate on educational
 expenses.
 High asset ownership gives income as well.
 That does not seem to be supported in the model.
 This is because high assets are meant to achieve a state desirable in itself.
 But it worth adding explicit security to assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
One trouble is that we are not sure if lower assets would increase risk-seeking
 behaviour or not.
 Lower payoff risk-seeking behaviour may increase due to low wealth.
 That wealth changes are relevant is a long tradition in behavioural economics
